hivebp. 7 (The servant in the house advertisement; address all communications to Film Booking Offices, Inc.)  aThe history of the British film, 1985:bv. 7, p. 194-195 (Columbia pictures made in U.S. distributed in Britain by Film Booking Offices, a British renter)  aMoon of Israel, c1927bDLC copy theater program, Roxy Theatre, New York, N.Y. performance ("Moon of Israel" distributed by F.B.O. Pictures Corporation)  aNeibaur, J.L. The RKO features, 1993:bCIP galley (in 1922, the Robertson-Cole Company became the Film Booking Office of America (FBO), which together with Keith-Albee-Orpheum [no publ. in LC], merged to form RKO Radio Pictures in 1929)  aIMDB, Jan. 20, 2011b(Film Booking Offices of America; FBO; motion picture production and distribution company; active 1917-1930)1 aThe Film Booking Offices of America (FBO) was a motion picture production and distribution company. Established in 1920 as the Robertson-Cole Company, it was reorganized as the Film Booking Offices in 1922. In 1928 the company merged with Keith-Albee-Orpheum to form Radio-Keith-Orpheum (RKO).03458cz  a2200385n  326933520220426065401.0810216n| azannaabn          |a ana        an  50082580   a(OCoLC)oca00116045  aDLCbengerdacDLCdDLCdNNCdUPBdDLCdUPBdHUdDLC  s1931t19572edtf2 aRKO Radio Pictures  aMotion picture industry2lcsh  aMotion pictures--Production and directionaMotion pictures--Distribution2lcsh2 aRadio Keith Orpheum Radio Pictures, inc.2 wnneaRKO Radio Pictures, inc.2 aRadio-Keith-Orpheum Corporation2 aRKO Distributing Corp.2 aRKO-Pathe2 aRKO General, inc.2 aRKO Productions2 wriProduct of merger:aRKO Teleradio Pictures  aThe exact relationship of the RKO film production and distribution companies was in flux during the early years of the company, and cannot be established conclusively.  aAnnie Oakley, 1935bcredits (RKO Radio Pictures presents)  aSlide, A. The new historical dictionary of the American film industry, 2001:bp. 173 (RKO Radio Pictures, Inc.; with the coming of sound, David Sarnoff, president of Radio Corporation of America (RCA), joined forces with Joseph P. Kennedy of Film Booking Offices of America (FBO). FBO was merged with the vaudeville circuit of Keith-Albee-Orpheum, which provided theatres in which to screen its product) p. 174 (RKO was sold to General Teleradio in 1955, though it continued to produce features through 1957)  aFilm daily year book, 1929 viewed August 17, 2020 via the Internet Archivebp. 854 (Radio-Keith-Orpheum Corp; R-K-O; in the fall of 1928 the Radio Corp. of America formed Radio-Keith-Orpheum to serve as a holding company for Keith-Albee-Orpheum, Film Booking Offices and RCA Photophone)  aFilm daily yearbook, 1936 viewed August 17, 2020 via the Internet Archivebp. 1018 (certain major assets of Pathe Exchange, Inc. were sold to RKO in 1931)  aIndia speaks ... c1933.  aNeibaur, J.L. The RKO features, 1993:bCIP t.p. (RKO Radio Pictures) galley (originated with Robertson-Cole Company, which in 1922, became Film Booking Office of America (FBO), which together with Keith-Albee-Orpheum [no publ. in LC], formed Radio Keith Orpheum, or RKO, in 1929; in 1955, sold to General Teleradio, inc.)  aMillie, 2000:bcredits (copyrighted by RKO Radio Pictures, Inc.; Radio Pictures)  aCopyright catalog, motion pictures, 1912-1939:bp. 543 (Millie, 1931; RKO Radio Pictures, Inc.; 6Feb31; LP1984)  aEncycl. Brittanica, via WWW, Jan. 13, 2011b(RKO Radio Pictures, Inc.; formed in merger of the Radio Corporation of America, Keith-Albee-Orpheum theatre chain, and American Pathé productions in 1928)1 aRKO Radio Pictures was a motion picture production and distribution company. The company was originally established in 1929 as Radio Pictures during the founding of Radio-Keith-Orpheum Corporation. In early 1931 some feature films were produced as Radio Pictures, but by the end of 1931, RKO Radio Pictures seems to have been the main producing entity. It also existed concurrently with RKO Pathe. In 1955 the company merged with General Teleradio to form RKO Teleradio Pictures, but continued to produce features through 1957.  aRETRO03573cz  a2200565n  188831920220423064536.0790521n| azannaabn          |b ana        an  79043101 zn  81129871 zsh 85144982   a(OCoLC)oca00276531  aDLCbengerdacDLCdDLCdDLC-HdDLCdOCoLCdUPBdWaUdIEN  s1929t19862 aWalt Disney Productions  aMotion picture studios2lcsh  cUnited States2naf  aMotion pictures--Production and direction2lcsh  aTelevision program production  aeng2 aDisney Film Recording Company2 aDisney Productions2 aDisney Studios0 wnnaaaDisney (Walt) Productions2 aUlpane Ṿolṭ Disni2 aUlpene Ṿolṭ Disni2 aṾolṭ Disni (Firm)2 aWalt Disney Studio2 aWalt Disney Studios (1929-1986)2 aאולפני וולט דיסני2 aאלפני וולט דיסני2 aוולד דיסני2 aוולט דיסני2 aסרטי וולט דיסני2 wriPredecessor:aDisney Brothers Studio2 wriPredecessor:aWalt Disney Enterprises2 wriPredecessor:aLiled Realty and Investment Company, ltd.2 wriSuccessor:aWalt Disney Company  aMachine-derived non-Latin script reference project.  aNon-Latin script references not evaluated.  aIts The adventures of Mickey Mouse, c1931.  aTel. call to Walt Disney Co., 3-20-87b(Walt Disney Productions changed its name to Walt Disney Company, 2-11-86)  aMilon li-ḳeṭanim temunot melamdot, 1981:bt.p. (Ṿolṭ Disni [voc.]) facing t.p. (Ulpane Ṿolṭ Disni [voc.])  aAristocats. Hebrew. Ḥatulim ba-tsameret, 1976:bt.p. (Ulpene Ṿolṭ Disni [voc.]) t.p. verso (Walt Disney Production)  aPhone call to Walt Disney Co. archives, 9/25/93b(Walt Disney Productions was incorporated in 1929, having previously been separate companies: Walt Disney Enterprises, Liled Realty and Investment Company, Disney Film Recording Company, Disney Brothers Studio; also known informally as Walt Disney Studio or Walt Disney Studios)  aWalt Disney's Good housekeep